Good call, let me add a few more:

Startup Studios (slight variation)
Some distinguish these from venture studios by focusing more on serial entrepreneurship - one founder or small team spinning up multiple companies sequentially rather than in parallel.

Pre-accelerators / Founder Programs
Programs designed to get you ready for an accelerator. Even earlier stage - helping you validate ideas, find co-founders, build MVPs. Often free or very cheap.

Micro-VCs / Rolling Funds
Not programs but funding vehicles - small funds that write smaller checks, often with a thesis around specific stages or sectors. More hands-on than traditional VC.

Entrepreneur-in-Residence (EIR) Programs
VCs or studios bring in experienced founders to explore ideas under their umbrella. The EIR gets salary + resources while searching for their next company.

Holding Companies / Startup Conglomerates
Think Tiny (Andrew Wilkinson) or Constellation Software - they acquire and operate multiple companies under one roof, but don't typically build from scratch.

Launchpads / Founder Houses
Physical co-living/co-working spaces where founders live together and build. More about environment than structured programming.

Fellowship Programs
Non-dilutive grants + community, like Thiel Fellowship, On Deck, or Pioneer. Focus on the person, not necessarily a specific company.

Government/EU Programs
Things like EIC Accelerator, regional development funds - grants and support without equity, but often with bureaucratic overhead.

DAOs / Web3 Incubators
Decentralized models where communities collectively fund and support projects.

